<promed@promedmail.org>
[Dr. Gould points out the recognized and well discussed dilemma with
respect to the interpretations of laboratory testing conducted for
identification of infection with the SARS associated coronavirus (SARS CoV)
-- the deficiencies in knowledge on the sensitivity and specificity of the
laboratory tests currently available. (Dr. Gould's comment was submitted
in response to the ProMED-mail posting on a suspected case of SARS in
Singapore "SARS - worldwide (169): Singapore, suspected, RFI
20030908.2249). The information from a letter to the editor of the Swiss
Medical Weekly by L Kaiser et al and provided by Chris Griot further
highlights how in the absence of a clear cut outbreak of SARS,
approximately 62 percent of patients clinically/epidemiologically
classified as potential SARS cases (including suspected, probable and
others with a history of epidemiologic potential exposure and an acute
respiratory illness) were found to have other viral etiologies for their
respiratory illness (a reminder of earlier definitions of SARS as "a
diagnosis of exclusion").
The New York Times article gives a good overview of the dilemma faced in
Canada following the initial laboratory reports that the SARS CoV (or
mutant) was the etiologic agent of an outbreak of mild respiratory illness
in a nursing home. This was later ruled out after further testing was
done. The points raised by Dr. MacKenzie in the interview with the NY
Times on the issues confronting the laboratories are very valid
points. First, the lack of quality assurance. The various methods have not
been tested in different laboratories under different conditions. Second,
there is no internationally accepted standardization of the reagents used
in testing in different laboratories. and third there is the need to look
very carefully at what is done if there is a laboratory positive case. He
also points out the crucial need of a second laboratory, preferably an
international reference laboratory outside the country that found the
positive, confirms the tests.
That being said, the probable case of SARS CoV infection being monitored
and investigated in Singapore right now will further add to the above
mentioned discussion as more information becomes available. At present the
initial laboratory tests have been validated by a second laboratory in the
same country. We await the results of further testing by an international
reference laboratory outside of Singapore. To use a popular expression ...
"To be continued........" - Mod.MPP]
